annotation.text:
== History ==
This ''swing'' formation was founded by [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/8ecae52e-9c89-4b61-99d8-ac11abc26771.html|Chick Webb] in the late 20s, from (and predating) the former ''Harlem Stoppers'' Webb's Quintet, and the [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/8411e79d-deba-4753-8cd3-b1d23a264050.html|Jungle Band].
During the early 30s, it was the ''Savoy Ballroom'' house band, and was dreaded as one of the ''Giants killer'' big band formation of the era (notably, the high-fly [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/83e79e85-ea3d-4fdf-9aa7-ee843d60e2bb.html|Goodman's orchestra] was dwarfed during one of these Savoy "battles").
Integrating [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/54799c0e-eb45-4eea-996d-c4d71a63c499.html|Ella Fitzgerald] in its rank in 1935, the band enjoyed wide popularity and a few charts success, before [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/8ecae52e-9c89-4b61-99d8-ac11abc26771.html|Webb]'s dramatic death in 1939.
[http://musicbrainz.org/artist/54799c0e-eb45-4eea-996d-c4d71a63c499.html|Ella Fitzgerald] then lead the band for two more years under the name [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/e67a956b-b7cd-4deb-b41e-461e976cd191.html|Ella Fitzgerald and Her Famous Orchestra], before going solo and splitting it up during the summer of 1941.
The band never really had ''stars'' in its rank (beside, of course, [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/54799c0e-eb45-4eea-996d-c4d71a63c499.html|Ella Fitzgerald], and quick appearances of [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/25cf5731-bed9-4604-97a4-8b9655de1a30.html|Benny Carter] and [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/881d33d8-e86f-42e8-b571-dbde156f6907.html|Johnny Hodges]) and its main strengths were its unity and [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/8ecae52e-9c89-4b61-99d8-ac11abc26771.html|Webb]'s amazing play.

A later [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/54799c0e-eb45-4eea-996d-c4d71a63c499.html|Ella Fitzgerald] release would "reunite" the former '''Webb Orchestra''' members during the 50s.

== Listener Guide ==

The band discography nowadays is available in two parts, the first (prior 1939) being detailed in [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/8ecae52e-9c89-4b61-99d8-ac11abc26771.html|Chick Webb's page], the second obviously found under [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/e67a956b-b7cd-4deb-b41e-461e976cd191.html|Ella Fitzgerald and Her Famous Orchestra], which modern editions tend to scatter into [http://musicbrainz.org/artist/54799c0e-eb45-4eea-996d-c4d71a63c499.html|Ella Fitzgerald] discography (in the numerous releases covering the early [http://musicbrainz.org/label/f18f3b31-8263-4de3-966a-fda317492d3d.html|Decca] days).

The reference for serious listeners is either the [http://musicbrainz.org/label/cf239f09-7ccf-4feb-8c09-eef7bdc22d27.html|Classics]' Chronological, or the [http://musicbrainz.org/label/b392f59c-7941-4574-be84-5a0b5bedf202.html|Proper]'s boxset.

== Additional Notes ==
The band was variously referred to as Chick Webb's Orchestra, Chick Webb and his Orchestra, Chick Webb's Band, Chick Webb and his Band, Chick Webb Savoy's Orchestra, etc.
There is absolutely no differences between these.
